<H2><A NAME="SECTION00002000000000000000">
Calculation of the Number of Unforgeable Sequences</A>
</H2>

<P>
We have a recurrence relation for <IMG
 WIDTH="45" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img9.png"
 ALT="$ F(n)$"> given by

<P>
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
F(n) = \left\{
\begin{tabular}{ll}
  $2$\  & for $n=1$\  \\
  $2 F(n-1) - F(n/2)$\  & for $n$\  even \\
  $2 F(n-1)$\  & otherwise. \\
\end{tabular}
\right.
\end{displaymath}
 -->
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="374" HEIGHT="88" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img12.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle F(n) = \left\{
\begin{tabular}{ll}
$2$\ &amp; for $n=1$\ \\
$2 F(n-1...
...F(n/2)$\ &amp; for $n$\ even \\
$2 F(n-1)$\ &amp; otherwise. \\
\end{tabular}\right.
$">
</DIV><P></P>
The proof is by induction on <IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img1.png"
 ALT="$ n$">.  The cases <IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img3.png"
 ALT="$ n = 1$"> and <IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img4.png"
 ALT="$ n = 2$"> are taken from
the previous tabulation.  Let us assume that the recurrence relation
holds for <IMG
 WIDTH="48" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img13.png"
 ALT="$ n-2$"> and <IMG
 WIDTH="48" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img14.png"
 ALT="$ n-1$">.

<P>
If <IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img1.png"
 ALT="$ n$"> is odd, we can put <!-- MATH
 $n = 2m + 1$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img15.png"
 ALT="$ n = 2m + 1$">.  Now the sequence of length n
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}, x_m, x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
\end{displaymath}
 -->
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="255" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img16.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}, x_m, x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
$">
</DIV><P></P>
is not forgeable if and only if the sequence of length <IMG
 WIDTH="48" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img14.png"
 ALT="$ n-1$">
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}, x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
\end{displaymath}
 -->
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="223" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img17.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}, x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
$">
</DIV><P></P>
is not forgeable (where <IMG
 WIDTH="28" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img18.png"
 ALT="$ x_m$"> can be either 0 or 1).  Therefore there
are two unforgeable sequences of length <IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img1.png"
 ALT="$ n$"> for every unforgeable
sequence of length <IMG
 WIDTH="48" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img14.png"
 ALT="$ n-1$">, that is, <!-- MATH
 $F(n) = 2 F(n-2)$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="153" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img19.png"
 ALT="$ F(n) = 2 F(n-2)$">.

<P>
If <IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img1.png"
 ALT="$ n$"> is even, we can put <IMG
 WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img20.png"
 ALT="$ n = 2 m$">.  It is sufficient to show that
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
F(n) = 4 F(n-2) - F(n/2)
\end{displaymath}
 -->
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="235" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img21.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle F(n) = 4 F(n-2) - F(n/2)
$">
</DIV><P></P>
It is clear that the sequence of length n
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}, x_m, x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
\end{displaymath}
 -->
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="255" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img16.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}, x_m, x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
$">
</DIV><P></P>
is not forgeable if and only if both

<OL>
<LI><A NAME="cond1"></A>the sequence of length <IMG
 WIDTH="48" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img13.png"
 ALT="$ n-2$">
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}, x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
\end{displaymath}
 -->
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="223" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img17.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}, x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
$">
</DIV><P></P>
is not forgeable and,
</LI>
<LI><A NAME="cond2"></A>the two sequences of length <IMG
 WIDTH="21" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img22.png"
 ALT="$ m$">
<!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}  \hbox{\rm\quad and\quad} x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
\end{displaymath}
 -->
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="283" HEIGHT="35" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img23.png"
 ALT="$\displaystyle x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1} \hbox{\rm\quad and\quad} x_{m+1}, ..., x_n
$">
</DIV><P></P>
are not the same.
</LI>
</OL>
The number of times condition&nbsp;(<A HREF="#cond1">1</A>) is satisfied is <IMG
 WIDTH="87" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img24.png"
 ALT="$ 4 F(n-2)$"> since
<IMG
 WIDTH="28" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img18.png"
 ALT="$ x_m$"> and <IMG
 WIDTH="45" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img25.png"
 ALT="$ x_{m+1}$"> may freely range over the values 0 and 1.  So it only
remains to show that the number of times condition&nbsp;(<A HREF="#cond1">1</A>) is satisfied
while condition&nbsp;(<A HREF="#cond2">2</A>) is not, is given by <IMG
 WIDTH="64" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img26.png"
 ALT="$ F(n/2)$">.  However, 
condition&nbsp;(<A HREF="#cond1">1</A>) is true
while condition&nbsp;(<A HREF="#cond2">2</A>) is not if and only if the following two 
subsidiary conditions are met

<OL>
<LI><!-- MATH
 $x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="122" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img27.png"
 ALT="$ x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m-1}$"> and <!-- MATH
 $x_{m+1}, ..., x_n$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img28.png"
 ALT="$ x_{m+1}, ..., x_n$">
are the same, and
</LI>
<LI>the sequence <!-- MATH
 $x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="105" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img29.png"
 ALT="$ x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m} $"> is unforgeable.
</LI>
</OL>
This happens <IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img30.png"
 ALT="$ F(m)$"> times as <!-- MATH
 $x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="105" HEIGHT="33" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img29.png"
 ALT="$ x_1, x_2, ..., x_{m} $"> range over all possible
values, and <!-- MATH
 $F(m) = F(n/2)$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="134" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img31.png"
 ALT="$ F(m) = F(n/2)$">.

<P>
